data.content:
Here are the modern MSTest replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.That.HasCount(users, 3);
    Assert.That.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));
    Assert.That.Contains(users, u => u.Role == "Admin");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Old | New | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.That.HasCount(users, 3)` | Exact count is stricter; also covers non-empty |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` | `Assert.That.AllSatisfy(...)` | Tells you *which* element failed |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.That.HasCount(users, 3)` | Clear failure message with expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.That.Contains(users, predicate)` | No need for `Single` + null check |

Other useful collection assertions from `Assert.That`:
- **`IsEmpty(collection)`** / **`IsNotEmpty(collection)`**
- **`ContainsEqual(collection, expected)`** — checks for a specific item
- **`HasCountGreaterThan(collection, n)`** — if you just need "at least one"
